name: fruit tree seedling production, for planting | fruit tree seedling, for planting | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/14983/documentation

The dataset refers to the production of 25600 of fruit tree seedlings which is the yield of 1 ha of one nursery period which lasts 824 days. This dataset refers to an average situation; for specific situations exchanges might differ substantially due to site specific parameters

The activity starts with the production of rootstocks and stems and the process of grafting. This activity includes agricultural machinery, mineral and organic fertilisers, pesticides and ground cultivation.


The dataset contains the production tree seedlings in a nursery for plantation in fruit tree orchards such as apple orchards. The seedlings are produced on the open field, without irrigation. Transport from the nursery to the farm is not included. The activity ends with a one year old tree seedling at the nursery ready to be sold for plantation in a fruit orchard.
category: A:Agriculture, forestry and fishing/01:Crop and animal production, hunting and related service activities/013:Plant propagation/0130:Plant propagation

processDocumentation.timeDescription: Time period referring to the data source: 2000-2000. Based on expert opinion data is considered to be valid at least up to 2012.
processDocumentation.dataTreatmentDescription: If used, extrapolations are documented on the flow level.
processDocumentation.samplingDescription:
Data were collected by contacting 3 nurseries in Switzerland. The sampling was carried out at Agroscope by Patrik Mouron and Franziska Heller.
Direct field emissions are calculated according to SALCA (Swiss Agricultural Life Cycle Assessment). Details can be taken from: T. Nemecek, R. F. Knuchel, M. Alig, G. Gaillard, 2010. The advantages of generic LCA tools for agriculture: example SALCAcrop and SALCAfarm). Proceeding of the 7th Int. conference on life cycle assessment in the agri-food sector, Bari, Italy, 22-24 September 2010, pp. 433-438
